if the macro support isn't included in the native-image test classpath, especially since `testRuntimeOnly sourceSets.macroSupport.output` is in play. It seems like `nativeTestCompile` might rely on `sourceSets.test.runtimeClasspath`. I need to clarify this further to ensure everything functions correctly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring build configuration**\\n\\nI’m digging into whether we can improve the build configuration to exclude the compiler from macroSupport runtime. Unfortunately, I can’t get that to work. I consider using `./gradlew tasks` but remember the user asked not to compile or run tests myself. \\n\\nI’ve looked into several call sites linking to the retrieveRuntimeModule and retrieveRuntimeField functionalities. I wonder if there are any issues with Java fields or whether the Scala compiler might optimize calls unexpectedly. It seems that using JsonCodecMaker may also have limitations regarding local dependencies.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing support class packaging**\\n\\nI’m considering that the needed package of support classes might be located in test packages, and user-code-filtering could be excluding everything else. It seems like dynamic access to support may not be tracked unless it involves library calls. For native images, I wonder if generated codecs reference MacroRuntimeNames, but it looks like the macro evaluates field names to constants instead. \\n\\nSo, perhaps the macroSupport runtime isn’t really necessary. I note potential issues with sourceSets and the order of test dependencies in build.gradle. Regarding test classes, I think using underscores might be a good idea, and I'll summarize everything concisely without running tests as instructed.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZUyhFJxbSwHIYzqovHHqyOlW|fc_05db16ac799a99ce0169f881b00dc4819c8add1fb2316144be", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/src